      <li><a href="#best-foods">The 20 Best High-Protein Foods</a></li>
      <li><a href="#meal-plan">3-Day High-Protein Meal Plan</a></li>
      <li><a href="#plant-based">Getting Enough Protein on a Plant-Based Diet</a></li>
      <li><a href="#timing">Does Protein Timing Matter?</a></li>
      <li><a href="#safety">Is High Protein Safe?</a></li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <h2 id="why-protein">Why Protein Matters More During Weight Loss</h2>
  <p>When you eat fewer calories than you burn, your body needs to find fuel from somewhere. Ideally, that fuel comes entirely from stored fat. In practice, some muscle is always lost during a deficit — but the amount of muscle lost is largely determined by two factors: how much protein you eat and whether you do resistance training.</p>
  <p>Protein protects muscle during a deficit through several mechanisms:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Provides amino acids for muscle protein synthesis</strong> — the ongoing process of repairing and building muscle fibres</li>
    <li><strong>Increases satiety</strong> — protein is the most satiating macronutrient, reducing hunger and making calorie restriction more sustainable</li>
    <li><strong>Raises the thermic effect of food</strong> — the body burns 20–30% of protein calories just in the process of digesting and metabolising it (vs 5–10% for carbs and 0–3% for fat)</li>
    <li><strong>Preserves metabolic rate</strong> — muscle loss lowers basal metabolic rate; preserving muscle by eating adequate protein prevents this decline</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Studies consistently show that higher protein intakes during calorie restriction produce better body composition outcomes — more fat lost, more muscle retained — compared to standard protein intakes, even when total calories are identical.</p>

  <h2 id="how-much">How Much Protein Do You Actually Need?</h2>
  <p>The general population recommendation of 0.8 g of protein per kg of body weight per day is a minimum to prevent deficiency — not an optimal amount for weight loss. For people in a calorie deficit who want to preserve muscle, the evidence supports significantly higher intakes:</p>

  <div class="card" style="padding:20px;margin:20px 0;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:12px;">
    <table class="bmi-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Goal</th><th>Protein target</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>General health</td><td>0.8 g/kg/day</td><td>Minimum to prevent deficiency</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Weight loss (moderate)</td><td>1.2–1.6 g/kg/day</td><td>Good baseline for most people</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Weight loss (optimal)</strong></td><td><strong>1.6–2.2 g/kg/day</strong></td><td><strong>Maximises muscle retention</strong></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Weight loss + heavy training</td><td>2.0–2.4 g/kg/day</td><td>For active individuals training 4+ days/week</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>Use lean body mass as your reference if you have a high body fat percentage. A 90 kg person with 40% body fat has a lean mass of 54 kg — targeting 2.2 g/kg of total weight (198 g) may be excessive; targeting 2.2 g/kg of lean mass (119 g) is more appropriate. Use our <a href="body-fat.html">Body Fat Calculator</a> to estimate lean mass and our <a href="macro-calculator.html">Macro Calculator</a> to get a personalised protein target.</p>

