    <p style="color:var(--ink3);font-size:.85rem;margin:0;"><strong>Total: ~156g protein · ~1,600 kcal</strong></p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="plant-based">Getting Enough Protein on a Plant-Based Diet</h2>
  <p>Hitting 1.6 g/kg of protein on a plant-based diet requires planning but is very achievable. Key strategies:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Prioritise complete protein sources:</strong> tofu, tempeh, edamame, seitan, quinoa, and soy milk all provide all essential amino acids</li>
    <li><strong>Combine complementary proteins:</strong> rice + lentils, hummus + wholegrain pitta, peanut butter + wholegrain bread — these combinations provide complete amino acid profiles</li>
    <li><strong>Build meals around protein:</strong> instead of adding protein as an afterthought, start meal planning with the protein source and build around it</li>
    <li><strong>Use protein-fortified foods:</strong> soy milk, high-protein pasta, and fortified plant milks can boost daily totals meaningfully</li>
    <li><strong>Consider pea or soy protein powder:</strong> these are complete proteins and are an efficient, affordable way to top up if food sources fall short</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout">
    <p><strong>Plant-based protein example:</strong> 200g firm tofu (16g) + 150g cooked lentils (14g) + 100g edamame (11g) + 200g soy yoghurt (8g) + 50g hemp seeds (16g) = <strong>65g protein from plants alone</strong> at breakfast and lunch. Achievable.</p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="timing">Does Protein Timing Matter?</h2>
  <p>The short answer: less than you've probably been told. The "anabolic window" — the idea that you must consume protein within 30 minutes of training — has been largely debunked for the general population. Total daily protein intake matters far more than timing.</p>
  <p>That said, there are a few evidence-supported timing principles worth following:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Spread protein across meals</strong> — 3–4 servings of 30–40g each stimulates muscle protein synthesis more effectively than front- or back-loading all your protein in one or two meals</li>
    <li><strong>Include protein at breakfast</strong> — morning protein intake is associated with better appetite control throughout the day</li>
    <li><strong>Consume protein within 2 hours of resistance training</strong> — the window is wider than once thought, but within 2 hours is a reasonable guideline</li>
    <li><strong>Casein protein before bed</strong> — slow-digesting protein (cottage cheese, casein powder, Greek yoghurt) before sleep may enhance overnight muscle protein synthesis</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="safety">Is High Protein Safe?</h2>
  <p>In healthy individuals, intakes up to 2.2 g/kg/day are well-supported by the evidence as safe. Multiple systematic reviews and meta-analyses have found no evidence of kidney damage, bone loss, or other adverse effects from high protein diets in people with normal kidney function.</p>
  <p><strong>Important exception:</strong> People with existing chronic kidney disease (CKD) should follow a <em>lower</em> protein diet as advised by their nephrologist — high protein intake accelerates decline in already-compromised kidneys. If you have CKD, do not follow the targets in this article without medical guidance.</p>
  <p>Adequate hydration is important on a high-protein diet — aim for the water intake calculated by our <a href="water-intake.html">Water Intake Calculator</a>, adjusted upward slightly if protein intake is very high.</p>

